410 auto LHSPointees = make_pointee_range(LHS); 0
411 auto RHSPointees = make_pointee_range(RHS); 0
412 return std::equal(LHSPointees.begin(), LHSPointees.end(), 0
413 RHSPointees.begin()); 0
414 } ----
415 ----
416 void MachineInstr::cloneMergedMemRefs(MachineFunction &MF, 0
417 ArrayRef MIs) { ----
418 // Try handling easy numbers of MIs with simpler mechanisms. ----
419 if (MIs.empty()) { 0
420 dropMemRefs(MF); 0
421 return; 0
422 } ----
423 if (MIs.size() == 1) { 0
424 cloneMemRefs(MF, *MIs[0]); 0
425 return; 0
426 } ----
427 // Because an empty memoperands list provides *no* information and must be ----
428 // handled conservatively (assuming the instruction can do anything), the only ----
429 // way to merge with it is to drop all other memoperands. ----
430 if (MIs[0]->memoperands_empty()) { 0
431 dropMemRefs(MF); 0
432 return; 0
433 } ----
434 ----
435 // Handle the general case. ----
436 SmallVector MergedMMOs; 0
437 // Start with the first instruction. ----
438 assert(&MF == MIs[0]->getMF() && 0
439 "Invalid machine functions when cloning memory references!"); ----
440 MergedMMOs.append(MIs[0]->memoperands_begin(), MIs[0]->memoperands_end()); 0
441 // Now walk all the other instructions and accumulate any different MMOs. ----
442 for (const MachineInstr &MI : make_pointee_range(MIs.slice(1))) { 0
443 assert(&MF == MI.getMF() && 0
444 "Invalid machine functions when cloning memory references!"); ----
445 ----
446 // Skip MIs with identical operands to the first. This is a somewhat ----
447 // arbitrary hack but will catch common cases without being quadratic. ----
448 // TODO: We could fully implement merge semantics here if needed. ----
449 if (hasIdenticalMMOs(MIs[0]->memoperands(), MI.memoperands())) 0
450 continue; 0
451 ----
452 // Because an empty memoperands list provides *no* information and must be ----
453 // handled conservatively (assuming the instruction can do anything), the ----
454 // only way to merge with it is to drop all other memoperands. ----
455 if (MI.memoperands_empty()) { 0
456 dropMemRefs(MF); 0
457 return; 0
458 } ----
459 ----
460 // Otherwise accumulate these into our temporary buffer of the merged state. ----
461 MergedMMOs.append(MI.memoperands_begin(), MI.memoperands_end()); 0
462 } ----
463 ----
464 setMemRefs(MF, MergedMMOs); 0
465 } 0

468 // Do nothing if old and new symbols are the same. ----
469 if (Symbol == getPreInstrSymbol()) 0
470 return; 0
471 ----
472 // If there was only one symbol and we're removing it, just clear info. ----
473 if (!Symbol && Info.is()) { 0
474 Info.clear(); 0
475 return; 0
476 } ----
477 ----
478 setExtraInfo(MF, memoperands(), Symbol, getPostInstrSymbol(), 0
479 getHeapAllocMarker(), getPCSections(), getCFIType()); ----
480 } ----

544 ----
545 uint32_t MachineInstr::copyFlagsFromInstruction(const Instruction &I) { 0
546 uint32_t MIFlags = 0; 0
547 // Copy the wrapping flags. ----
548 if (const OverflowingBinaryOperator *OB = 0
549 dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
550 if (OB->hasNoSignedWrap()) 0
551 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoSWrap; 0
552 if (OB->hasNoUnsignedWrap()) 0
553 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoUWrap; 0
554 } ----
555 ----
556 // Copy the exact flag. ----
557 if (const PossiblyExactOperator *PE = dyn_cast(&I)) 0
558 if (PE->isExact()) 0
559 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::IsExact; 0
560 ----
561 // Copy the fast-math flags. ----
562 if (const FPMathOperator *FP = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
563 const FastMathFlags Flags = FP->getFastMathFlags(); 0
564 if (Flags.noNaNs()) 0
565 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmNoNans; 0
566 if (Flags.noInfs()) 0
567 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmNoInfs; 0
568 if (Flags.noSignedZeros()) 0
569 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmNsz; 0
570 if (Flags.allowReciprocal()) 0
571 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmArcp; 0
572 if (Flags.allowContract()) 0
573 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmContract; 0
574 if (Flags.approxFunc()) 0
575 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmAfn; 0
576 if (Flags.allowReassoc()) 0
577 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::FmReassoc; 0
578 } ----
579 ----
580 if (I.getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_unpredictable)) 0
581 MIFlags |= MachineInstr::MIFlag::Unpredictable; 0
582 ----
583 return MIFlags; 0
584 } ----
585 ----
586 void MachineInstr::copyIRFlags(const Instruction &I) { 0
587 Flags = copyFlagsFromInstruction(I); 0
588 } 0

605 ----
606 bool MachineInstr::isIdenticalTo(const MachineInstr &Other, 0
607 MICheckType Check) const { ----
608 // If opcodes or number of operands are not the same then the two ----
609 // instructions are obviously not identical. ----
610 if (Other.getOpcode() != getOpcode() || 0
611 Other.getNumOperands() != getNumOperands()) 0
612 return false; 0
613 ----
614 if (isBundle()) { 0
615 // We have passed the test above that both instructions have the same ----
616 // opcode, so we know that both instructions are bundles here. Let's compare ----
617 // MIs inside the bundle. ----
618 assert(Other.isBundle() && "Expected that both instructions are bundles."); 0
619 MachineBasicBlock::const_instr_iterator I1 = getIterator(); 0
620 MachineBasicBlock::const_instr_iterator I2 = Other.getIterator(); 0
621 // Loop until we analysed the last intruction inside at least one of the ----
622 // bundles. ----
623 while (I1->isBundledWithSucc() && I2->isBundledWithSucc()) { 0
624 ++I1; 0
625 ++I2; 0
626 if (!I1->isIdenticalTo(*I2, Check)) 0
627 return false; 0
628 } ----
629 // If we've reached the end of just one of the two bundles, but not both, ----
630 // the instructions are not identical. ----
631 if (I1->isBundledWithSucc() || I2->isBundledWithSucc()) 0
632 return false; 0
633 } ----
634 ----
635 // Check operands to make sure they match. ----
636 for (unsigned i = 0, e = getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) { 0
637 const MachineOperand &MO = getOperand(i); 0
638 const MachineOperand &OMO = Other.getOperand(i); 0
639 if (!MO.isReg()) { 0
640 if (!MO.isIdenticalTo(OMO)) 0
641 return false; 0
642 continue; 0
643 } ----
644 ----
645 // Clients may or may not want to ignore defs when testing for equality. ----
646 // For example, machine CSE pass only cares about finding common ----
647 // subexpressions, so it's safe to ignore virtual register defs. ----
648 if (MO.isDef()) { 0
649 if (Check == IgnoreDefs) 0
650 continue; 0
651 else if (Check == IgnoreVRegDefs) { 0
652 if (!MO.getReg().isVirtual() || !OMO.getReg().isVirtual()) 0
653 if (!MO.isIdenticalTo(OMO)) 0
654 return false; 0
655 } else { ----
656 if (!MO.isIdenticalTo(OMO)) 0
657 return false; 0
658 if (Check == CheckKillDead && MO.isDead() != OMO.isDead()) 0
659 return false; 0
660 } ----
661 } else { ----
662 if (!MO.isIdenticalTo(OMO)) 0
663 return false; 0
664 if (Check == CheckKillDead && MO.isKill() != OMO.isKill()) 0
665 return false; 0
666 } ----
667 } ----
668 // If DebugLoc does not match then two debug instructions are not identical. ----
669 if (isDebugInstr()) 0
670 if (getDebugLoc() && Other.getDebugLoc() && 0
671 getDebugLoc() != Other.getDebugLoc()) 0
672 return false; 0
673 // If pre- or post-instruction symbols do not match then the two instructions ----
674 // are not identical. ----
675 if (getPreInstrSymbol() != Other.getPreInstrSymbol() || 0
676 getPostInstrSymbol() != Other.getPostInstrSymbol()) 0
677 return false; 0
678 // Call instructions with different CFI types are not identical. ----
679 if (isCall() && getCFIType() != Other.getCFIType()) 0
680 return false; 0
681 ----
682 return true; 0
683 } ----
684 ----
685 bool MachineInstr::isEquivalentDbgInstr(const MachineInstr &Other) const { 0
686 if (!isDebugValueLike() || !Other.isDebugValueLike()) 0
687 return false; 0
688 if (getDebugLoc() != Other.getDebugLoc()) 0
689 return false; 0
690 if (getDebugVariable() != Other.getDebugVariable()) 0
691 return false; 0
692 if (getNumDebugOperands() != Other.getNumDebugOperands()) 0
693 return false; 0
694 for (unsigned OpIdx = 0; OpIdx < getNumDebugOperands(); ++OpIdx) 0
695 if (!getDebugOperand(OpIdx).isIdenticalTo(Other.getDebugOperand(OpIdx))) 0
696 return false; 0
697 if (!DIExpression::isEqualExpression( 0
698 getDebugExpression(), isIndirectDebugValue(), 0
699 Other.getDebugExpression(), Other.isIndirectDebugValue())) 0
700 return false; 0
701 return true; 0
702 } ----

746 ----
747 unsigned MachineInstr::getNumExplicitOperands() const { 0
748 unsigned NumOperands = MCID->getNumOperands(); 0
749 if (!MCID->isVariadic()) 0
750 return NumOperands; 0
751 ----
752 for (unsigned I = NumOperands, E = getNumOperands(); I != E; ++I) { 0
753 const MachineOperand &MO = getOperand(I); 0
754 // The operands must always be in the following order: ----
755 // - explicit reg defs, ----
756 // - other explicit operands (reg uses, immediates, etc.), ----
757 // - implicit reg defs ----
758 // - implicit reg uses ----
759 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isImplicit()) 0
760 break; 0
761 ++NumOperands; 0
762 } ----
763 return NumOperands; 0
764 } ----
765 ----
766 unsigned MachineInstr::getNumExplicitDefs() const { 0
767 unsigned NumDefs = MCID->getNumDefs(); 0
768 if (!MCID->isVariadic()) 0
769 return NumDefs; 0
770 ----
771 for (unsigned I = NumDefs, E = getNumOperands(); I != E; ++I) { 0
772 const MachineOperand &MO = getOperand(I); 0
773 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef() || MO.isImplicit()) 0
774 break; 0
775 ++NumDefs; 0
776 } ----
777 return NumDefs; 0
778 } ----

830 ----
831 int MachineInstr::findInlineAsmFlagIdx(unsigned OpIdx, 0
832 unsigned *GroupNo) const { ----
833 assert(isInlineAsm() && "Expected an inline asm instruction"); 0
834 assert(OpIdx < getNumOperands() && "OpIdx out of range"); 0
835 ----
836 // Ignore queries about the initial operands. ----
837 if (OpIdx < InlineAsm::MIOp_FirstOperand) 0
838 return -1; 0
839 ----
840 unsigned Group = 0; 0
841 unsigned NumOps; ----
842 for (unsigned i = InlineAsm::MIOp_FirstOperand, e = getNumOperands(); i < e; 0
843 i += NumOps) { 0
844 const MachineOperand &FlagMO = getOperand(i); 0
845 // If we reach the implicit register operands, stop looking. ----
846 if (!FlagMO.isImm()) 0
847 return -1; 0
848 NumOps = 1 + InlineAsm::getNumOperandRegisters(FlagMO.getImm()); 0
849 if (i + NumOps > OpIdx) { 0
850 if (GroupNo) 0
851 *GroupNo = Group; 0
852 return i; 0
853 } ----
854 ++Group; 0
855 } ----
856 return -1; 0
857 } ----

899 ----
900 const TargetRegisterClass* ----
901 MachineInstr::getRegClassConstraint(unsigned OpIdx, 0
902 const TargetInstrInfo *TII, ----
903 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const { ----
904 assert(getParent() && "Can't have an MBB reference here!"); 0
905 assert(getMF() && "Can't have an MF reference here!"); 0
906 const MachineFunction &MF = *getMF(); 0
907 ----
908 // Most opcodes have fixed constraints in their MCInstrDesc. ----
909 if (!isInlineAsm()) 0
910 return TII->getRegClass(getDesc(), OpIdx, TRI, MF); 0
911 ----
912 if (!getOperand(OpIdx).isReg()) 0
913 return nullptr; 0
914 ----
915 // For tied uses on inline asm, get the constraint from the def. ----
916 unsigned DefIdx; ----
917 if (getOperand(OpIdx).isUse() && isRegTiedToDefOperand(OpIdx, &DefIdx)) 0
918 OpIdx = DefIdx; 0
919 ----
920 // Inline asm stores register class constraints in the flag word. ----
921 int FlagIdx = findInlineAsmFlagIdx(OpIdx); 0
922 if (FlagIdx < 0) 0
923 return nullptr; 0
924 ----
925 unsigned Flag = getOperand(FlagIdx).getImm(); 0
926 unsigned RCID; ----
927 if ((InlineAsm::getKind(Flag) == InlineAsm::Kind_RegUse || 0
928 InlineAsm::getKind(Flag) == InlineAsm::Kind_RegDef || 0
929 InlineAsm::getKind(Flag) == InlineAsm::Kind_RegDefEarlyClobber) && 0
930 InlineAsm::hasRegClassConstraint(Flag, RCID)) 0
931 return TRI->getRegClass(RCID); 0
932 ----
933 // Assume that all registers in a memory operand are pointers. ----
934 if (InlineAsm::getKind(Flag) == InlineAsm::Kind_Mem) 0
935 return TRI->getPointerRegClass(MF); 0
936 ----
937 return nullptr; 0
938 } ----
939 ----
940 const TargetRegisterClass *MachineInstr::getRegClassConstraintEffectForVReg( 0
941 Register Reg, const TargetRegisterClass *CurRC, const TargetInstrInfo *TII, ----
942 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI, bool ExploreBundle) const { ----
943 // Check every operands inside the bundle if we have ----
944 // been asked to. ----
945 if (ExploreBundle) 0
946 for (ConstMIBundleOperands OpndIt(*this); OpndIt.isValid() && CurRC; 0
947 ++OpndIt) 0
948 CurRC = OpndIt->getParent()->getRegClassConstraintEffectForVRegImpl( 0
949 OpndIt.getOperandNo(), Reg, CurRC, TII, TRI); ----
950 else ----
951 // Otherwise, just check the current operands. ----
952 for (unsigned i = 0, e = NumOperands; i < e && CurRC; ++i) 0
953 CurRC = getRegClassConstraintEffectForVRegImpl(i, Reg, CurRC, TII, TRI); 0
954 return CurRC; 0
955 } ----
956 ----
957 const TargetRegisterClass *MachineInstr::getRegClassConstraintEffectForVRegImpl( 0
958 unsigned OpIdx, Register Reg, const TargetRegisterClass *CurRC, ----
959 const TargetInstrInfo *TII, const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const { ----
960 assert(CurRC && "Invalid initial register class"); 0
961 // Check if Reg is constrained by some of its use/def from MI. ----
962 const MachineOperand &MO = getOperand(OpIdx); 0
963 if (!MO.isReg() || MO.getReg() != Reg) 0
964 return CurRC; 0
965 // If yes, accumulate the constraints through the operand. ----
966 return getRegClassConstraintEffect(OpIdx, CurRC, TII, TRI); 0

1105 // MachineOperand::TiedTo is 4 bits wide. ----
1106 const unsigned TiedMax = 15; ----
1107 ----
1108 /// tieOperands - Mark operands at DefIdx and UseIdx as tied to each other. ----
1109 /// ----
1110 /// Use and def operands can be tied together, indicated by a non-zero TiedTo ----
1111 /// field. TiedTo can have these values: ----
1112 /// ----
1113 /// 0: Operand is not tied to anything. ----
1114 /// 1 to TiedMax-1: Tied to getOperand(TiedTo-1). ----
1115 /// TiedMax: Tied to an operand >= TiedMax-1. ----
1116 /// ----
1117 /// The tied def must be one of the first TiedMax operands on a normal ----
1118 /// instruction. INLINEASM instructions allow more tied defs. ----
1119 /// ----
1120 void MachineInstr::tieOperands(unsigned DefIdx, unsigned UseIdx) { 0
1121 MachineOperand &DefMO = getOperand(DefIdx); 0
1122 MachineOperand &UseMO = getOperand(UseIdx); 0
1123 assert(DefMO.isDef() && "DefIdx must be a def operand"); 0
1124 assert(UseMO.isUse() && "UseIdx must be a use operand"); 0
1125 assert(!DefMO.isTied() && "Def is already tied to another use"); 0
1126 assert(!UseMO.isTied() && "Use is already tied to another def"); 0
1127 ----
1128 if (DefIdx < TiedMax) 0
1129 UseMO.TiedTo = DefIdx + 1; 0
1130 else { ----
1131 // Inline asm can use the group descriptors to find tied operands, ----
1132 // statepoint tied operands are trivial to match (1-1 reg def with reg use), ----
1133 // but on normal instruction, the tied def must be within the first TiedMax ----
1134 // operands. ----
1135 assert((isInlineAsm() || getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT) && 0
1136 "DefIdx out of range"); ----
1137 UseMO.TiedTo = TiedMax; 0
1138 } ----
1139 ----
1140 // UseIdx can be out of range, we'll search for it in findTiedOperandIdx(). ----
1141 DefMO.TiedTo = std::min(UseIdx + 1, TiedMax); 0
1142 } 0
1143 ----
1144 /// Given the index of a tied register operand, find the operand it is tied to. ----
1145 /// Defs are tied to uses and vice versa. Returns the index of the tied operand ----
1146 /// which must exist. ----
1147 unsigned MachineInstr::findTiedOperandIdx(unsigned OpIdx) const { 0
1148 const MachineOperand &MO = getOperand(OpIdx); 0
1149 assert(MO.isTied() && "Operand isn't tied"); 0
1150 ----
1151 // Normally TiedTo is in range. ----
1152 if (MO.TiedTo < TiedMax) 0
1153 return MO.TiedTo - 1; 0
1154 ----
1155 // Uses on normal instructions can be out of range. ----
1156 if (!isInlineAsm() && getOpcode() != TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT) { 0
1157 // Normal tied defs must be in the 0..TiedMax-1 range. ----
1158 if (MO.isUse()) 0
1159 return TiedMax - 1; 0
1160 // MO is a def. Search for the tied use. ----
1161 for (unsigned i = TiedMax - 1, e = getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) { 0
1162 const MachineOperand &UseMO = getOperand(i); 0
1163 if (UseMO.isReg() && UseMO.isUse() && UseMO.TiedTo == OpIdx + 1) 0
1164 return i; 0
1165 } ----
1166 llvm_unreachable("Can't find tied use"); 0
1167 } ----
1168 ----
1169 if (getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT) { 0
1170 // In STATEPOINT defs correspond 1-1 to GC pointer operands passed ----
1171 // on registers. ----
1172 StatepointOpers SO(this); 0
1173 unsigned CurUseIdx = SO.getFirstGCPtrIdx(); 0
1174 assert(CurUseIdx != -1U && "only gc pointer statepoint operands can be tied"); 0
1175 unsigned NumDefs = getNumDefs(); 0
1176 for (unsigned CurDefIdx = 0; CurDefIdx < NumDefs; ++CurDefIdx) { 0
1177 while (!getOperand(CurUseIdx).isReg()) 0
1178 CurUseIdx = StackMaps::getNextMetaArgIdx(this, CurUseIdx); 0
1179 if (OpIdx == CurDefIdx) 0
1180 return CurUseIdx; 0
1181 if (OpIdx == CurUseIdx) 0
1182 return CurDefIdx; 0
1183 CurUseIdx = StackMaps::getNextMetaArgIdx(this, CurUseIdx); 0
1184 } ----
1185 llvm_unreachable("Can't find tied use"); 0
1186 } ----
1187 ----
1188 // Now deal with inline asm by parsing the operand group descriptor flags. ----
1189 // Find the beginning of each operand group. ----
1190 SmallVector GroupIdx; 0
1191 unsigned OpIdxGroup = ~0u; 0
1192 unsigned NumOps; ----
1193 for (unsigned i = InlineAsm::MIOp_FirstOperand, e = getNumOperands(); i < e; 0
1194 i += NumOps) { 0
1195 const MachineOperand &FlagMO = getOperand(i); 0
1196 assert(FlagMO.isImm() && "Invalid tied operand on inline asm"); 0
1197 unsigned CurGroup = GroupIdx.size(); 0
1198 GroupIdx.push_back(i); 0
1199 NumOps = 1 + InlineAsm::getNumOperandRegisters(FlagMO.getImm()); 0
1200 // OpIdx belongs to this operand group. ----
1201 if (OpIdx > i && OpIdx < i + NumOps) 0
1202 OpIdxGroup = CurGroup; 0
1203 unsigned TiedGroup; ----
1204 if (!InlineAsm::isUseOperandTiedToDef(FlagMO.getImm(), TiedGroup)) 0
1205 continue; 0
1206 // Operands in this group are tied to operands in TiedGroup which must be ----
1207 // earlier. Find the number of operands between the two groups. ----
1208 unsigned Delta = i - GroupIdx[TiedGroup]; 0
1209 ----
1210 // OpIdx is a use tied to TiedGroup. ----
1211 if (OpIdxGroup == CurGroup) 0
1212 return OpIdx - Delta; 0
1213 ----
1214 // OpIdx is a def tied to this use group. ----
1215 if (OpIdxGroup == TiedGroup) 0
1216 return OpIdx + Delta; 0
1217 } ----
1218 llvm_unreachable("Invalid tied operand on inline asm"); 0
1219 } 0

1250 /// isSafeToMove - Return true if it is safe to move this instruction. If ----
1251 /// SawStore is set to true, it means that there is a store (or call) between ----
1252 /// the instruction's location and its intended destination. ----
1253 bool MachineInstr::isSafeToMove(AAResults *AA, bool &SawStore) const { 0
1254 // Ignore stuff that we obviously can't move. ----
1255 // ----
1256 // Treat volatile loads as stores. This is not strictly necessary for ----
1257 // volatiles, but it is required for atomic loads. It is not allowed to move ----
1258 // a load across an atomic load with Ordering > Monotonic. ----
1259 if (mayStore() || isCall() || isPHI() || 0
1260 (mayLoad() && hasOrderedMemoryRef())) { 0
1261 SawStore = true; 0
1262 return false; 0
1263 } ----
1264 ----
1265 if (isPosition() || isDebugInstr() || isTerminator() || 0
1266 mayRaiseFPException() || hasUnmodeledSideEffects()) 0
1267 return false; 0
1268 ----
1269 // See if this instruction does a load. If so, we have to guarantee that the ----
1270 // loaded value doesn't change between the load and the its intended ----
1271 // destination. The check for isInvariantLoad gives the target the chance to ----
1272 // classify the load as always returning a constant, e.g. a constant pool ----
1273 // load. ----
1274 if (mayLoad() && !isDereferenceableInvariantLoad()) 0
1275 // Otherwise, this is a real load. If there is a store between the load and ----
1276 // end of block, we can't move it. ----
1277 return !SawStore; 0
1278 ----
1279 return true; 0
1280 } ----
1281 ----
1282 static bool MemOperandsHaveAlias(const MachineFrameInfo &MFI, AAResults *AA, 0
1283 bool UseTBAA, const MachineMemOperand *MMOa, ----
1284 const MachineMemOperand *MMOb) { ----
1285 // The following interface to AA is fashioned after DAGCombiner::isAlias and ----
1286 // operates with MachineMemOperand offset with some important assumptions: ----
1287 // - LLVM fundamentally assumes flat address spaces. ----
1288 // - MachineOperand offset can *only* result from legalization and cannot ----
1289 // affect queries other than the trivial case of overlap checking. ----
1290 // - These offsets never wrap and never step outside of allocated objects. ----
1291 // - There should never be any negative offsets here. ----
1292 // ----
1293 // FIXME: Modify API to hide this math from "user" ----
1294 // Even before we go to AA we can reason locally about some memory objects. It ----
1295 // can save compile time, and possibly catch some corner cases not currently ----
1296 // covered. ----
1297 ----
1298 int64_t OffsetA = MMOa->getOffset(); 0
1299 int64_t OffsetB = MMOb->getOffset(); 0
1300 int64_t MinOffset = std::min(OffsetA, OffsetB); 0
1301 ----
1302 uint64_t WidthA = MMOa->getSize(); 0
1303 uint64_t WidthB = MMOb->getSize(); 0
1304 bool KnownWidthA = WidthA != MemoryLocation::UnknownSize; 0
1305 bool KnownWidthB = WidthB != MemoryLocation::UnknownSize; 0
1306 ----
1307 const Value *ValA = MMOa->getValue(); 0
1308 const Value *ValB = MMOb->getValue(); 0
1309 bool SameVal = (ValA && ValB && (ValA == ValB)); 0
1310 if (!SameVal) { 0
1311 const PseudoSourceValue *PSVa = MMOa->getPseudoValue(); 0
1312 const PseudoSourceValue *PSVb = MMOb->getPseudoValue(); 0
1313 if (PSVa && ValB && !PSVa->mayAlias(&MFI)) 0
1314 return false; 0
1315 if (PSVb && ValA && !PSVb->mayAlias(&MFI)) 0
1316 return false; 0
1317 if (PSVa && PSVb && (PSVa == PSVb)) 0
1318 SameVal = true; 0
1319 } ----
1320 ----
1321 if (SameVal) { 0
1322 if (!KnownWidthA || !KnownWidthB) 0
1323 return true; 0
1324 int64_t MaxOffset = std::max(OffsetA, OffsetB); 0
1325 int64_t LowWidth = (MinOffset == OffsetA) ? WidthA : WidthB; 0
1326 return (MinOffset + LowWidth > MaxOffset); 0
1327 } ----
1328 ----
1329 if (!AA) 0
1330 return true; 0
1331 ----
1332 if (!ValA || !ValB) 0
1333 return true; 0
1334 ----
1335 assert((OffsetA >= 0) && "Negative MachineMemOperand offset"); 0
1336 assert((OffsetB >= 0) && "Negative MachineMemOperand offset"); 0
1337 ----
1338 int64_t OverlapA = 0
1339 KnownWidthA ? WidthA + OffsetA - MinOffset : MemoryLocation::UnknownSize; 0
1340 int64_t OverlapB = 0
1341 KnownWidthB ? WidthB + OffsetB - MinOffset : MemoryLocation::UnknownSize; 0
1342 ----
1343 return !AA->isNoAlias( 0
1344 MemoryLocation(ValA, OverlapA, UseTBAA ? MMOa->getAAInfo() : AAMDNodes()), 0
1345 MemoryLocation(ValB, OverlapB, 0
1346 UseTBAA ? MMOb->getAAInfo() : AAMDNodes())); 0
1347 } ----
1348 ----
1349 bool MachineInstr::mayAlias(AAResults *AA, const MachineInstr &Other, 0
1350 bool UseTBAA) const { ----
1351 const MachineFunction *MF = getMF(); 0
1352 const TargetInstrInfo *TII = MF->getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
1353 const MachineFrameInfo &MFI = MF->getFrameInfo(); 0
1354 ----
1355 // Exclude call instruction which may alter the memory but can not be handled ----
1356 // by this function. ----
1357 if (isCall() || Other.isCall()) 0
1358 return true; 0
1359 ----
1360 // If neither instruction stores to memory, they can't alias in any ----
1361 // meaningful way, even if they read from the same address. ----
1362 if (!mayStore() && !Other.mayStore()) 0
1363 return false; 0
1364 ----
1365 // Both instructions must be memory operations to be able to alias. ----
1366 if (!mayLoadOrStore() || !Other.mayLoadOrStore()) 0
1367 return false; 0
1368 ----
1369 // Let the target decide if memory accesses cannot possibly overlap. ----
1370 if (TII->areMemAccessesTriviallyDisjoint(*this, Other)) 0
1371 return false; 0
1372 ----
1373 // Memory operations without memory operands may access anything. Be ----
1374 // conservative and assume `MayAlias`. ----
1375 if (memoperands_empty() || Other.memoperands_empty()) 0
1376 return true; 0
1377 ----
1378 // Skip if there are too many memory operands. ----
1379 auto NumChecks = getNumMemOperands() * Other.getNumMemOperands(); 0
1380 if (NumChecks > TII->getMemOperandAACheckLimit()) 0
1381 return true; 0
1382 ----
1383 // Check each pair of memory operands from both instructions, which can't ----
1384 // alias only if all pairs won't alias. ----
1385 for (auto *MMOa : memoperands()) 0
1386 for (auto *MMOb : Other.memoperands()) 0
1387 if (MemOperandsHaveAlias(MFI, AA, UseTBAA, MMOa, MMOb)) 0
1388 return true; 0
1389 ----
1390 return false; 0
1391 } ----
1392 ----
1393 /// hasOrderedMemoryRef - Return true if this instruction may have an ordered ----
1394 /// or volatile memory reference, or if the information describing the memory ----
1395 /// reference is not available. Return false if it is known to have no ordered ----
1396 /// memory references. ----
1397 bool MachineInstr::hasOrderedMemoryRef() const { 11 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1398 // An instruction known never to access memory won't have a volatile access. ----
1399 if (!mayStore() && 11 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1400 !mayLoad() && 4 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1401 !isCall() && 15 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1402 !hasUnmodeledSideEffects()) 0
1403 return false; 0
1404 ----
1405 // Otherwise, if the instruction has no memory reference information, ----
1406 // conservatively assume it wasn't preserved. ----
1407 if (memoperands_empty()) 11 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1408 return true; 0
1409 ----
1410 // Check if any of our memory operands are ordered. ----
1411 return llvm::any_of(memoperands(), [](const MachineMemOperand *MMO) { 22 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1412 return !MMO->isUnordered(); 11 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1413 }); 11 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1414 } ----
1415 ----
1416 /// isDereferenceableInvariantLoad - Return true if this instruction will never ----
1417 /// trap and is loading from a location whose value is invariant across a run of ----
1418 /// this function. ----
1419 bool MachineInstr::isDereferenceableInvariantLoad() const { 0
1420 // If the instruction doesn't load at all, it isn't an invariant load. ----
1421 if (!mayLoad()) 0
1422 return false; 0
1423 ----
1424 // If the instruction has lost its memoperands, conservatively assume that ----
1425 // it may not be an invariant load. ----
1426 if (memoperands_empty()) 0
1427 return false; 0
1428 ----
1429 const MachineFrameInfo &MFI = getParent()->getParent()->getFrameInfo(); 0
1430 ----
1431 for (MachineMemOperand *MMO : memoperands()) { 0
1432 if (!MMO->isUnordered()) 0
1433 // If the memory operand has ordering side effects, we can't move the ----
1434 // instruction. Such an instruction is technically an invariant load, ----
1435 // but the caller code would need updated to expect that. ----
1436 return false; 0
1437 if (MMO->isStore()) return false; 0
1438 if (MMO->isInvariant() && MMO->isDereferenceable()) 0
1439 continue; 0
1440 ----
1441 // A load from a constant PseudoSourceValue is invariant. ----
1442 if (const PseudoSourceValue *PSV = MMO->getPseudoValue()) { 0
1443 if (PSV->isConstant(&MFI)) 0
1444 continue; 0
1445 } ----
1446 ----
1447 // Otherwise assume conservatively. ----
1448 return false; 0
1449 } ----
1450 ----
1451 // Everything checks out. ----
1452 return true; 0
1453 } ----
1454 ----
1455 /// isConstantValuePHI - If the specified instruction is a PHI that always ----
1456 /// merges together the same virtual register, return the register, otherwise ----
1457 /// return 0. ----
1458 unsigned MachineInstr::isConstantValuePHI() const { 0

1509 ----
1510 bool MachineInstr::hasComplexRegisterTies() const { 0
1511 const MCInstrDesc &MCID = getDesc(); 0
1512 if (MCID.Opcode == TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT) 0
1513 return true; 0
1514 for (unsigned I = 0, E = getNumOperands(); I < E; ++I) { 0
1515 const auto &Operand = getOperand(I); 0
1516 if (!Operand.isReg() || Operand.isDef()) 0
1517 // Ignore the defined registers as MCID marks only the uses as tied. ----
1518 continue; 0
1519 int ExpectedTiedIdx = MCID.getOperandConstraint(I, MCOI::TIED_TO); 0
1520 int TiedIdx = Operand.isTied() ? int(findTiedOperandIdx(I)) : -1; 0
1521 if (ExpectedTiedIdx != TiedIdx) 0
1522 return true; 0
1523 } ----
1524 return false; 0
1525 } ----

1527 LLT MachineInstr::getTypeToPrint(unsigned OpIdx, SmallBitVector &PrintedTypes, 0
1528 const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI) const { ----
1529 const MachineOperand &Op = getOperand(OpIdx); 0
1530 if (!Op.isReg()) 0
1531 return LLT{}; 0
1532 ----
1533 if (isVariadic() || OpIdx >= getNumExplicitOperands()) 0
1534 return MRI.getType(Op.getReg()); 0
1535 ----
1536 auto &OpInfo = getDesc().operands()[OpIdx]; 0
1537 if (!OpInfo.isGenericType()) 0
1538 return MRI.getType(Op.getReg()); 0
1539 ----
1540 if (PrintedTypes[OpInfo.getGenericTypeIndex()]) 0
1541 return LLT{}; 0
1542 ----
1543 LLT TypeToPrint = MRI.getType(Op.getReg()); 0
1544 // Don't mark the type index printed if it wasn't actually printed: maybe ----
1545 // another operand with the same type index has an actual type attached: ----
1546 if (TypeToPrint.isValid()) 0
1547 PrintedTypes.set(OpInfo.getGenericTypeIndex()); 0
1548 return TypeToPrint; 0
1549 } ----

1557 LLVM_DUMP_METHOD void MachineInstr::dumprImpl( 0
